    <h1 style="text-align: center;">INTERMEDIATE</h1>
    <p>Intermediate education, often referred to as secondary education, typically encompasses grades 11 and 12 in many educational systems.
         This stage follows primary or elementary education and precedes higher education (college or university). Here's a general overview:
        
        
         <h2>Key Aspects of Intermediate Education:</h2>
        
            <h3>Age Group:</h3> Students in intermediate education are usually between 16 to 18 years old.
        
            <h3>Curriculum:</h3> The curriculum is more specialized compared to primary education. Students can often choose specific streams or subjects 
            based on their interests and career aspirations. Common streams include:

            <h3>Science:</h3> Focuses on subjects like Physics, Chemistry, Biology, and Mathematics.
            <h3>Commerce:</h3> Includes subjects like Economics, Business Studies, Accounting, and Mathematics.
            <h3>Humanities/Arts:</h3> Covers subjects like History, Political Science, Sociology, and Literature.
            <h3>Vocational Courses:</h3> Some systems offer vocational training in fields like IT, healthcare, and hospitality.
        
            <h3>Examinations:</h3> Intermediate education often culminates in board examinations or standardized tests that play a crucial role in determining students' eligibility for higher education or employment opportunities.
        
            <h3>Career Guidance:</h3> This stage often includes career counseling to help students make informed decisions about their future education and career paths.
        
            <h3>Skill Development:</h3> In addition to academic knowledge, there is often a focus on developing life skills, critical thinking, and communication skills.
        
            <h3>Global Perspective:</h3> Intermediate education may also emphasize global awareness and understanding of cultural diversity, preparing students for a globalized world.
        
        <h2>Importance of Intermediate Education:</h2>
        
            Foundation for Higher Education: It serves as a bridge between basic education and higher studies, laying the groundwork for professional courses and specialization.
        <h3>Personal Growth:</h3> This phase is crucial for personal development, as students gain independence, responsibility, and a sense of identity.
        <h3>Career Pathways:</h3> Choices made during this stage can significantly influence career trajectories.</p>
